        <div id="era-content">
            
            <section id="grunge" class="era-section active">
                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-amber-600 mb-4">The Grunge Explosion (Early 1990s)</h2>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 mb-6">Emerging from the rain-soaked Pacific Northwest, Grunge was a visceral reaction against the glam and excess of 1980s rock. It was a raw, unfiltered sound that captured the angst and disillusionment of a generation. This section explores the key characteristics, influential bands, and the factors that led to both the meteoric rise and the tragic, sudden decline of this pivotal movement.</p>
                    
                    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
                        <div>
                            <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2 text-slate-700">Sonic & Lyrical DNA</h3>
                            <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-slate-600">
                                <li><strong>Sound:</strong> Raw, lo-fi production fusing punk's energy with heavy metal's sludgy, distorted guitar riffs.</li>
                                <li><strong>Vocals:</strong> Angst-ridden, often gravelly or screaming, conveying deep emotional turmoil.</li>
                                <li><strong>Themes:</strong> Social alienation, apathy, confinement, depression, and a cynical view of societal norms.</li>
                                <li><strong>Aesthetic:</strong> Anti-fashion ethos defined by thrift-store finds like flannel shirts, ripped jeans, and combat boots.</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2 text-slate-700">Factors in its Fall</h3>
                            <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-slate-600">
                                <li><strong>Commercialization:</strong> The music industry co-opted the "alternative" label, diluting its authenticity.</li>
                                <li><strong>Loss of Icons:</strong> The death of Kurt Cobain in 1994 was a devastating blow that symbolized the end of the era.</li>
                                <li><strong>Substance Abuse:</strong> Widespread drug use took a heavy toll on many of the scene's key musicians.</li>
                                <li><strong>Audience Fatigue:</strong> The relentless darkness and angst of the genre led to burnout among listeners.</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-800 mb-4 text-center">Key Bands of the Era</h3>
                    <div class="grid grid-cols-2 md:grid-cols-4 gap-4">
                        <div class="band-card relative overflow-hidden rounded-lg shadow-md group">
                            <img src="https://placehold.co/600x400/1e293b/f59e0b?text=Nirvana" alt="Nirvana" class="w-full h-full object-cover">
                            <div class="info absolute bottom-0 left-0 w-full bg-black bg-opacity-75 text-white p-3">
                                <h4 class="font-bold">Nirvana</h4>
                                <p class="text-xs">Brought grunge to the masses with "Smells Like Teen Spirit," becoming the reluctant voice of a generation.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="band-card relative overflow-hidden rounded-lg shadow-md group">
                            <img src="https://placehold.co/600x400/1e293b/f59e0b?text=Pearl+Jam" alt="Pearl Jam" class="w-full h-full object-cover">
                            <div class="info absolute bottom-0 left-0 w-full bg-black bg-opacity-75 text-white p-3">
                                <h4 class="font-bold">Pearl Jam</h4>
                                <p class="text-xs">Known for their arena-rock sensibilities, passionate vocals, and long-lasting career beyond the grunge peak.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="band-card relative overflow-hidden rounded-lg shadow-md group">
                           <img src="https://placehold.co/600x400/1e293b/f59e0b?text=Soundgarden" alt="Soundgarden" class="w-full h-full object-cover">
                            <div class="info absolute bottom-0 left-0 w-full bg-black bg-opacity-75 text-white p-3">
                                <h4 class="font-bold">Soundgarden</h4>
                                <p class="text-xs">Pioneers of the Seattle sound, blending heavy metal and punk with Chris Cornell's iconic vocal range.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="band-card relative overflow-hidden rounded-lg shadow-md group">
                            <img src="https://placehold.co/600x400/1e293b/f59e0b?text=Alice+in+Chains" alt="Alice in Chains" class="w-full h-full object-cover">
                            <div class="info absolute bottom-0 left-0 w-full bg-black bg-opacity-75 text-white p-3">
                                <h4 class="font-bold">Alice in Chains</h4>
                                <p class="text-xs">The darkest of the "big four," known for their sludgy riffs and haunting vocal harmonies exploring themes of addiction.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>

            <section id="post-grunge" class="era-section">
                 <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-amber-600 mb-4">The Post-Grunge Polish (Mid-late 1990s)</h2>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 mb-6">After the fall of grunge's original titans, the music industry sought a more palatable, radio-friendly version of the sound. Post-Grunge was born, sanding down the rough edges of its predecessor while retaining the distorted guitars and general aesthetic. This section examines how the genre evolved, its two distinct waves, and the criticisms it faced for its perceived lack of authenticity.</p>
                    
                    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
                        <div>
                            <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2 text-slate-700">Sonic & Lyrical DNA</h3>
                            <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-slate-600">
                                <li><strong>Sound:</strong> Cleaner, polished production. More conventional song structures (verse-chorus-verse).</li>
                                <li><strong>Vocals:</strong> Retained a gravelly tone but were generally more melodic and less chaotic.</li>
                                <li><strong>Themes:</strong> Shifted from societal angst to more personal, direct topics like relationships and romance.</li>
                                <li><strong>Commercial Appeal:</strong> Designed for mainstream radio, balancing aggressive rockers with power ballads.</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                           <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2 text-slate-700">Key Distinctions</h3>
                            <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-slate-600">
                                <li><strong>First Wave (e.g., Bush):</strong> More directly emulated the sound and feel of the original grunge bands.</li>
                                <li><strong>Second Wave (e.g., Creed):</strong> Achieved massive commercial success with a more formulaic, anthemic approach.</li>
                                <li><strong>Criticism:</strong> Often derided as a "watered-down" or "corporate" version of grunge, lacking its raw spirit.</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-800 mb-4 text-center">Key Bands of the Era</h3>
                    <div class="grid grid-cols-2 md:grid-cols-4 gap-4">
                        <div class="band-card relative overflow-hidden rounded-lg shadow-md group">
                            <img src="https://placehold.co/600x400/334155/f59e0b?text=Foo+Fighters" alt="Foo Fighters" class="w-full h-full object-cover">
                            <div class="info absolute bottom-0 left-0 w-full bg-black bg-opacity-75 text-white p-3">
                                <h4 class="font-bold">Foo Fighters</h4>
                                <p class="text-xs">Formed by Nirvana's Dave Grohl, they bridged the gap with a more optimistic and accessible hard rock sound.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="band-card relative overflow-hidden rounded-lg shadow-md group">
                            <img src="https://placehold.co/600x400/334155/f59e0b?text=Bush" alt="Bush" class="w-full h-full object-cover">
                            <div class="info absolute bottom-0 left-0 w-full bg-black bg-opacity-75 text-white p-3">
                                <h4 class="font-bold">Bush</h4>
                                <p class="text-xs">A British band that found huge success in the US by closely emulating the Seattle sound.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="band-card relative overflow-hidden rounded-lg shadow-md group">
                           <img src="https://placehold.co/600x400/334155/f59e0b?text=Creed" alt="Creed" class="w-full h-full object-cover">
                            <div class="info absolute bottom-0 left-0 w-full bg-black bg-opacity-75 text-white p-3">
                                <h4 class="font-bold">Creed</h4>
                                <p class="text-xs">Became one of the biggest bands in the world, defining the second wave with their anthemic, earnest rock.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="band-card relative overflow-hidden rounded-lg shadow-md group">
                           <img src="https://placehold.co/600x400/334155/f59e0b?text=Nickelback" alt="Nickelback" class="w-full h-full object-cover">
                            <div class="info absolute bottom-0 left-0 w-full bg-black bg-opacity-75 text-white p-3">
                                <h4 class="font-bold">Nickelback</h4>
                                <p class="text-xs">Achieved immense commercial success but also faced significant backlash, becoming synonymous with the genre's formulaic criticisms.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>
            
            <section id="emo-metalcore" class="era-section">
                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-amber-600 mb-4">The Emo & Metalcore Ascension (Late 1990s - Mid 2000s)</h2>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 mb-6">As post-grunge settled into a comfortable radio formula, a more emotionally charged and aggressive movement was capturing the youth. Emo, Post-Hardcore, and Metalcore took the introspection of grunge and amplified it, creating a new cultural phenomenon. This section delves into the sonic and thematic shifts that defined this era, which prized raw vulnerability and technical intensity over mainstream polish.</p>

                    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
                        <div>
                            <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2 text-slate-700">Sonic & Lyrical DNA</h3>
                            <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-slate-600">
                                <li><strong>Emo Sound:</strong> Highly dynamic, shifting from quiet, melodic verses to loud, passionate choruses. Often pop-punk influenced.</li>
                                <li><strong>Metalcore Sound:</strong> A fusion of hardcore punk and extreme metal, known for aggressive screamed verses, melodic clean choruses, and "breakdowns."</li>
                                <li><strong>Themes:</strong> Deeply personal and confessional lyrics about heartbreak, anxiety, depression, and identity.</li>
                                <li><strong>Subculture:</strong> A strong connection between bands and fans, with a distinct fashion aesthetic and online community (e.g., MySpace).</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2 text-slate-700">The New Face of Angst</h3>
                            <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-slate-600">
                                <li><strong>Vulnerability:</strong> A departure from post-grunge's macho posturing, embracing open emotional expression.</li>
                                <li><strong>Screamo:</strong> A more intense offshoot of emo, characterized by chaotic song structures and consistent screamed vocals.</li>
                                <li><strong>Mainstream Breakout:</strong> Bands like My Chemical Romance and Fall Out Boy brought emo to the forefront of pop culture.</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-800 mb-4 text-center">Key Bands of the Era</h3>
                    <div class="grid grid-cols-2 md:grid-cols-4 gap-4">
                        <div class="band-card relative overflow-hidden rounded-lg shadow-md group">
                           <img src="https://placehold.co/600x400/475569/f59e0b?text=My+Chemical+Romance" alt="My Chemical Romance" class="w-full h-full object-cover">
                            <div class="info absolute bottom-0 left-0 w-full bg-black bg-opacity-75 text-white p-3">
                                <h4 class="font-bold">My Chemical Romance</h4>
                                <p class="text-xs">The quintessential emo band of the era, known for their theatricality and concept albums.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="band-card relative overflow-hidden rounded-lg shadow-md group">
                            <img src="https://placehold.co/600x400/475569/f59e0b?text=Fall+Out+Boy" alt="Fall Out Boy" class="w-full h-full object-cover">
                            <div class="info absolute bottom-0 left-0 w-full bg-black bg-opacity-75 text-white p-3">
                                <h4 class="font-bold">Fall Out Boy</h4>
                                <p class="text-xs">Brought a pop-punk sensibility and witty, verbose lyrics to the emo scene, achieving massive chart success.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="band-card relative overflow-hidden rounded-lg shadow-md group">
                            <img src="https://placehold.co/600x400/475569/f59e0b?text=Killswitch+Engage" alt="Killswitch Engage" class="w-full h-full object-cover">
                            <div class="info absolute bottom-0 left-0 w-full bg-black bg-opacity-75 text-white p-3">
                                <h4 class="font-bold">Killswitch Engage</h4>
                                <p class="text-xs">Pioneers of melodic metalcore, perfecting the blend of brutal verses and soaring, clean choruses.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="band-card relative overflow-hidden rounded-lg shadow-md group">
                            <img src="https://placehold.co/600x400/475569/f59e0b?text=Thursday" alt="Thursday" class="w-full h-full object-cover">
                            <div class="info absolute bottom-0 left-0 w-full bg-black bg-opacity-75 text-white p-3">
                                <h4 class="font-bold">Thursday</h4>
                                <p class="text-xs">A key band in bringing screamo and post-hardcore to a wider audience with their influential album "Full Collapse."</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>
            
            <section id="decline" class="era-section">
                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-lg">
                    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-amber-600 mb-4">The Mainstream Decline (Late 2000s)</h2>
                    <p class="text-slate-600 mb-6">History often repeats itself in music. Just as grunge had before, the emo and metalcore movements eventually faded from the mainstream spotlight. A combination of over-saturation, cultural shifts, and changing musical tastes led to the end of their chart dominance. This final section explores the factors that contributed to the decline of this era of rock.</p>

                    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
                        <div>
                            <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2 text-slate-700">Reasons for the Fade</h3>
                            <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-slate-600">
                                <li><strong>Genre Oversaturation:</strong> The market became flooded with bands copying the successful formula, leading to listener fatigue.</li>
                                <li><strong>Commercialization of the "Scene":</strong> The emo subculture and fashion became a mainstream trend, losing its counter-cultural edge and authenticity.</li>
                                <li><strong>Shifting Musical Landscape:</strong> The rise of indie rock, dance-pop, and hip-hop drew mainstream attention away from guitar-centric rock.</li>
                                <li><strong>"Emo Revival":</strong> A subsequent movement saw a return to the genre's less commercial, 1990s indie roots, but it remained largely an underground scene.</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2 text-slate-700">The Legacy</h3>
                            <p class="text-slate-600">While no longer dominating the charts, the impact of these genres remains. They provided a voice for a generation, brought discussions of mental health to the forefront in rock music, and influenced countless modern artists. The passion of their fanbases continues, and periodic reunion tours and "emo nights" attest to their lasting cultural significance.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>
        </div>
    </main>

    <script>
        document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function () {
            const navButtons = document.querySelectorAll('#era-nav .nav-button');
            const eraSections = document.querySelectorAll('.era-section');

            navButtons.forEach(button => {
                button.addEventListener('click', () => {
                    const targetEra = button.dataset.era;
                    
                    navButtons.forEach(btn => btn.classList.remove('active'));
                    button.classList.add('active');

                    eraSections.forEach(section => {
                        if (section.id === targetEra) {
                            section.classList.add('active');
                        } else {
                            section.classList.remove('active');
                        }
                    });
                });
            });

            const chartCtx = document.getElementById('eras-chart').getContext('2d');
            const erasChart = new Chart(chartCtx, {
                type: 'line',
                data: {
                    labels: ['1991', '1993', '1995', '1997', '1999', '2001', '2003', '2005', '2007', '2009'],
                    datasets: [{
                        label: 'Grunge',
                        data: [20, 80, 50, 20, 10, 5, 5, 5, 5, 5],
                        borderColor: 'rgba(245, 158, 11, 1)',
                        backgroundColor: 'rgba(245, 158, 11, 0.2)',
                        fill: true,
                        tension: 0.4
                    }, {
                        label: 'Post-Grunge',
                        data: [5, 15, 40, 70, 85, 80, 60, 40, 30, 20],
                        borderColor: 'rgba(51, 65, 85, 1)',
                        backgroundColor: 'rgba(51, 65, 85, 0.2)',
                        fill: true,
                        tension: 0.4
                    }, {
                        label: 'Emo/Metalcore',
                        data: [0, 0, 5, 10, 20, 40, 70, 90, 75, 40],
                        borderColor: 'rgba(239, 68, 68, 1)',
                        backgroundColor: 'rgba(239, 68, 68, 0.2)',
                        fill: true,
                        tension: 0.4
                    }]
                },
                options: {
                    responsive: true,
                    maintainAspectRatio: false,
                    plugins: {
                        legend: {
                            position: 'top',
                        },
                        title: {
                            display: false,
                            text: 'Mainstream Popularity Over Time'
                        },
                        tooltip: {
                           mode: 'index',
                           intersect: false,
                        },
                    },
                    scales: {
                        y: {
                            beginAtZero: true,
                            title: {
                                display: true,
                                text: 'Relative Mainstream Popularity'
                            }
                        },
                        x: {
                             title: {
                                display: true,
                                text: 'Year'
                            }
                        }
                    },
                    interaction: {
                        mode: 'index',
                        intersect: false,
                    }
                }
            });
        });
    </script>

